SIMPLE: shorten
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shorten
<hw>Short"en</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Shortened</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Shortening</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Short</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make short or shorter in
measure, extent, or time; <as>as, to <ex>shorten</ex> distance; to
<ex>shorten</ex> a road; to <ex>shorten</ex> days of
calamity.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To reduce or diminish in amount, quantity, or
extent; to lessen; to abridge; to curtail; to contract; <as>as, to
<ex>shorten</ex> work, an allowance of food, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here, where the subject is so fruitful, I am <qex>shortened</qex>
by my chain.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make deficient (as to); to deprive; -- with
<xex>of</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Spoiled of his nose, and <qex>shortened</qex> of his ears.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To make short or friable, as pastry, with butter,
lard, pot liquor, or the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To shorten a rope</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to
take in the slack of it.</cd> -- <col><b>To shorten sail</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to reduce sail by taking it in.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shorten</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shorten
<hw>Short"en</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become short or shorter;
<as>as, the day <ex>shortens</ex> in northern latitudes from June to
December; a metallic rod <ex>shortens</ex> by cold.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shortener</ent>⟦br⟧
